on and maintenance of the urban community just as much as the city's physical buildings. Sound in this space triggered a wide variety of social behaviors and spatial relations: hierarchical, personal, communal, political, domestic, sexual, spiritual, and religious.By exploring these rarely studied soundscapes, Atkinson shows Florence to be both an exceptional and an exemplary case study of urban conditions in the early modern period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArchitectural acousticsxHistoryxItalyxFlorence. 0aArchitectural acousticsxHistory. 0aArchitecture, RenaissancexItalyxFlorence. 0aArchitecture, RenaissancezItalyzFlorence. 0aBellsxHistoryxItalyxFlorence. 0aBellszItalyzFlorencexHistory. 0aCity soundsxHistoryxItalyxFlorence. 0aCity soundszItalyzFlorencexHistory. 0aRenaissancexItalyxFlorence. 0aRenaissancezItalyzFlorence. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074524540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271077833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271077833.jpg  a978-3-11-074524-5  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK